Problem:
Group a list of strings by their lengths.
Input:
List<String> words = Arrays.asList("cat", "house", "bird", "dog");

Solutions:

Java 8 Streams group strings by length using Collectors.groupingBy(String::length). For input ["cat", "house", "bird", "dog"] (lengths 3,5,4,3), produces {3=["cat", "dog"], 4=["bird"], 5=["house"]}.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream words via stream(). Collect with groupingBy(String::length) creating Map<Integer, List<String>>.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class GroupByLength {
    public static Map<Integer, List<String>> groupByLength(List<String> words) {
        return words.stream()
                    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(String::length));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> words = Arrays.asList("cat", "house", "bird", "dog");
        Map<Integer, List<String>> grouped = groupByLength(words);
        System.out.println(grouped);
    }
}

Prints {3=[cat, dog], 4=[bird], 5=[house]} (HashMap order varies).

#Thought Process
groupingBy(classifier) partitions by key (length); default toList() downstream. String::length concise key extractor. Single-pass O(n).

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty Map.
Null list: NPE.
Null elements: Key null.length() NPE; filter.
Empty strings: Group {0=[ ]}.
All same length: {len=[all]}.
